  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 30.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - The meaning of the precept in this verse is clear. We are nat to strive or quarrel with a man unless he has first given us offence. So Le Clerc, \"Nisi injuria prior lacessiverit.\" The admonition is directed against those who, from spite, jealousy, or other reasons, \"stir up strife all the day long\" with those who are quiet and peaceable. Strive. The Keri here reads ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "tariv",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for the Khetib ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "taruv",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but without any change of meaning. The verb ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "ruv",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", from which ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "taruv",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is \"to strive or contend with the hand and with blows,\" as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 33:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; or with words, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 103:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (cf. the Vulgate, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "ne contendas",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and the LXX, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "μὴ φιλεχθήσης",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"Do not exercise enmity,\" from the unusual ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "φιλεχθρέω",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Ruv",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is here followed by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "עִם",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "im",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 9:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 40:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 26:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Its forensic sense, \"to contend with in law,\" does not strictly apply here, though the precept may be taken as discouraging litigation (Lapide). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Without cause",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "khinnam",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); LXX., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ματήν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", equivalent to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "δωρεάν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 15:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; Vulgate, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "frustra",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; further explained in the concluding clause (see on Proverbs 1:17). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "If he have done thee no harm.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The phrase, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "gumal raah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is to bring evil upon any one (Schultens). The verb ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "gamal",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " signifies \"to do, to give, to show to any one.\" Holdea renders, \"Surely he will return thee evil,\" in the sense that unprovoked attack ensures retaliation.]gut this is to ignore the negative force of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "im-lo",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"if not.\" The verb sometimes means \"requiting,\" but not in the passage before us, nor in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 11:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 31:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Vulgate renders as the Authorized Version, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Cum ipse tibi nihil mali fecerit.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " It is to be remarked that this precept falls below the moral standard of the New Testament teaching (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 5:39-41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 12:17-21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 6:6-8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and of the example of our Lord, of whom it was predicted that \"When he was reviled, be reviled not again; when he suffered, he threatened not\" (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 53",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Proverbs 3:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
